ohnhly\nwould result In putting railroad em\nployment back on a nine or ten-hour\nhttsis, and the peak and slack period*\nWould pncouiiter tbe same old employ\nment problem. It Would be possible.\nOf course, as Daniel Willard has\npointed out. merely to extend the\nworking hours during rush jieriiids in\norder to prevent employment of ad\nditional men. Hut from a labor stand\npoint the experiment would he dan\ngerous.\nThe elglit-hour day, won through\nlung years of effort on the part of\norganized labor, has come to lie a\nrecognized fixture in industry. That\n11 hns been a forward step no one can\ndeny. It 1ms given workers some\nthing more out of life, bus made daily\nexistence more tolerable for the eoun.\ntry ns a whole, and has not curtailed\nproduction. There is no reason to he\nHeve it hns impaired railroad effl\ncineey. Any surrender of tbe prin\nciple of tbe eight-hour day. now so\nfirmly entrenclu-d. would h\u00ab> a step\nI nick ward, not only for labor, but for\nludstry.\nFARM-REMKF ATHTTDK\nIt is to be regfetted that sentiment\ncm farm relief legislation, expresed\nMonday at the Xorthwestern Agrieul\nttiijal conference at St. Haul, was\ntjiiiffilmously in favor of the principles\nmlKxfled in the MuXary-Hagen bill,\n*itoed last winter by President f'ool\nidge.\n;If the agricultural Interests are to\nlijsist cm legislation of this character,\nthere Is little possibility of anything\n\u2022constructive being done for the farm\ning industry. It might be possible to\nwhipsaw one or tbe other of the great\nppliticul parties Into acceptance of\nsiiich n program, and for legislation of\nthis type eventually to find its way\ni\u00abto tbe federal statutes. Hut the\nfarmers will find out to their sorrow.\nIf ever this day comes, that legislation\nof the type sought never will meet thi\nnned.\n5S3SHBBSH3I^^gg=li?lE==g=?igir==\nIn substance the MeNnry-Hnngen\nbill undertook to guarantee the farm*\nor profitable marketing of bis crop,\nl! in create an artificial1\n